@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "6. Header Element";
}

<div class="container">
    <h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>

    <p>The <code>&lt;header&gt;</code> element, like it sounds, is used to identify the top of a page, article, section, or other segment of a page. In general, the <code>&lt;header&gt;</code> element may include a heading, introductory text, and even navigation.</p>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">HTML Example</div>
        <div class="code-content">
<pre><code class="language-html">
&lt;header&gt;
  &lt;h1&gt;Welcome to My Website&lt;/h1&gt;
  &lt;p&gt;Your source for all things HTML&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/header&gt;
</code></pre>
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>&lt;header&gt; vs. &lt;head&gt; vs. &lt;h1&gt; - &lt;h6&gt; Elements</h2>

    <ul>
        <li>
            The <code>&lt;header&gt;</code> element is a <strong>structural element</strong> that outlines the heading of a segment of a page. It falls within the <code>&lt;body&gt;</code> element.
        </li>
        <li>
            The <code>&lt;head&gt;</code> element is <strong>not displayed</strong> on a page and is used to outline metadata, including the document title and links to external files. It falls directly within the <code>&lt;html&gt;</code> element.
        </li>
        <li>
            Heading elements, <code>&lt;h1&gt;</code> through <code>&lt;h6&gt;</code>, are used to designate <strong>multiple levels of text headings</strong> throughout a page.
        </li>
    </ul>

    <div class="navigation-buttons">
        <a href="@Url.Action("BuildingStructure", "Frontend")" class="btn btn-outline-primary">← Building Structure</a>
        <a href="@Url.Action("NavElement", "Frontend")" class="btn btn-primary">Navigation Element →</a>
    </div>
</div>

